Government expenditure (from taxes and transfers) on sanitation and drinking-water ranged from 0.37% to 3.5% of GDP (Figure 3.2).
Summary data from respondent countries indicate that median government expenditure on sanitation and drinking-water is one third of that for health and one sixth of that for education (Table 3.4).
One third of countries indicate that revenues cover less than 80% of operating costs for urban utilities (Figure 3.11).
Aid commitments to water and sanitation remained at 4.7% (US$ 7.8 billion) of total reported development aid in 2010 (Figure 6.1).

Aid for drinking-water and sanitation has risen slowly as a percentage of total development aid since the low point of 2002, but is still significantly below aid for social sectors, such as health and education (Figure 6.2).
Multiple factors influence donor aid prioritization (Figure 6.6).
Development aid for sanitation and drinking-water to fragile and conflict-affected states increased by 50% from US$ 560 million to US$ 840 million from 2007 to 2010 (Figure 6.7).
